Title: FileHandle.stream

Body:
It might be possible to have a more efficient way to pipe a file to a stream by adding a `.stream` method to `FileHandle`.

e.g.

```js

FileHandle.prototype.stream = async function (dst, { start = 0, end, signal } = {}) {
 // TODO: this[kRef](), this[kUnref](), if (signal.aborted) throw AbortError()
  let pos = start
  while (true) {
    if (end && pos >= end) {
      break
    }
  
    const { buffer, bytesRead } = await this.read({
      buffer: Buffer.allocUnsafe(Math.min(end - pos, 16384)),
      position: pos,
    })
  
    if (bytesRead === 0) {
      break
    }
  
    if (dst.writableNeedDrain) {
      await EE.once(res, 'drain', { signal })
    }
  
    if (dst.destroyed) {
      break // TODO: break or throw?
    }
  
    dst.write(buffer)
  
    pos += bytesRead
  }
}
```

```js
const fileHandle = fsp.open(filePath)
try {
  await fileHandle.stream(dst)
} finally {
  await fileHandle.close()
}
```

vs

```js
await pipeline(fs.createReadStream(filePath), dst)
```

Less ergonomic but potentially better performance. This idea needs benchmarking.

body:
The issue occurs when adding a variable with undefined in one of the object and in another object doesn't exist the property, for example:

```js
const a = {
  b: 1,
}


const b = {
  a: undefined,
  b: 1,
}

assert.deepEqual(a, b)
```


<!--
Thank you for reporting an issue.

This issue tracker is for bugs and issues found within Node.js core.
If you require more general support please file an issue on our help
repo. https://github.com/nodejs/help


Please fill in as much of the template below as you're able.

Version: output of `node -v`
Platform: output of `uname -a` (UNIX), or output of `"$([Environment]::OSVersion | ForEach-Object VersionString) $(if ([Environment]::Is64BitOperatingSystem) { "x64" } else { "x86" })"` in PowerShell console (Windows)
Subsystem: if known, please specify affected core module name
-->

* **Version**: v12.13.1
* **Platform**: masOs Catalina version 10.15.7
* **Subsystem**:

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Complete example:

```js
const deepCompare = (a, b) => {
  try {
    assert.deepEqual(a, b)
  } catch(e) {
    console.log('actual: ', JSON.stringify(e.actual, null, 2))
    console.log('expected: ', JSON.stringify(e.expected, null, 2))
  }
}

const a = {
  b: 1,
}


const b = {
  a: undefined,
  b: 1,
}

deepCompare(a , b)

/*

Result:

actual:  {
  "b": 1
}
expected:  {
  "b": 1
}

The result is showing the actual and the expected are the same object
*/

```

<!--
Enter details about your bug, preferably a simple code snippet that can be
run using `node` directly without installing third-party dependencies.
-->

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

always ;)

### What is the expected behavior?

Basically, I think is a confusing case because the actual and the expected are equals in the error so we need to find a mechanism to avoid this error or show an error with more consistency

`fs/promises` should provide all the features of `fs`, not only the the promisified versions of the callback functions, to stop relying on `require('fs')`.
This way, only a `require('fs/promises')` would be needed for newer programs.

Currently, we should rely on a double import:

```javascript
const pipeline = require('stream/promises');
const fsPromises = require('fs/promises');
const fsNonPromise = require('fs');

await fsPromises.mkdir('test');
await pipeline(fsNonPromise.createWriteStream('test/out.txt'), ...);
```

This would be easier:
```javascript
const pipeline = require('stream/promises');
const fs = require('fs/promises');

await fs.mkdir('test');
await pipeline(fs.createWriteStream('test/out.txt'), ...);
```

The functions for which a promisified version wouldn't make sense (like `createWriteStream`) should be included as is in `fs/promises`.
I'm not sure about the `*Sync` versions of the fs functions.

text:
Title: Add fs.createReadStream & fs.createWriteStream to fs.promises

Body:
`fs/promises` should provide all the features of `fs`, not only the the promisified versions of the callback functions, to stop relying on `require('fs')`.
This way, only a `require('fs/promises')` would be needed for newer programs.

Currently, we should rely on a double import:

```javascript
const pipeline = require('stream/promises');
const fsPromises = require('fs/promises');
const fsNonPromise = require('fs');

await fsPromises.mkdir('test');
await pipeline(fsNonPromise.createWriteStream('test/out.txt'), ...);
```

This would be easier:
```javascript
const pipeline = require('stream/promises');
const fs = require('fs/promises');

await fs.mkdir('test');
await pipeline(fs.createWriteStream('test/out.txt'), ...);
```

The functions for which a promisified version wouldn't make sense (like `createWriteStream`) should be included as is in `fs/promises`.
I'm not sure about the `*Sync` versions of the fs functions.

