Title: utils.type.isCallSite() method

Body:
<!--
Thank you for suggesting an idea to make Node.js better.

Please fill in as much of the template below as you're able.
-->

**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

`require('util').types` provides `is...` methods for all "exotic" object types.

One which is missing is detection of `CallSite` objects.

`CallSite` objects can accessed with [callsites](https://www.npmjs.com/package/callsites) NPM package or created with:

```js
Error.prepareStackTrace = (_, stack) => stack;
const obj = {};
Error.captureStackTrace(obj);
const callSite = obj.stack[0];
```

Use cases are probably fairly slim, but `util.types` appears to aim to cover all exotic object types, so I think it would make sense to plug this gap.

**Describe the solution you'd like**

A `types.isCallSite()` method.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**

The following works, and cannot be fooled if the value's prototype has been altered with `Object.setPrototypeOf()`. However, it's ugly and probably rather slow.

NB Most of the other `types.is` functions could also be replicated in much the same way, so in my view the presence of this workaround isn't reason for not having this in core.

```js
const CallSite = ( () => {
  const obj = {};
  const { prepareStackTrace } = Error;
  Error.prepareStackTrace = ( _, stack ) => stack;
  Error.captureStackTrace( obj );
  const CallSite = obj.stack[0].constructor;
  Error.prepareStackTrace = prepareStackTrace;
  return CallSite;
} )();

function isCallSite( value ) {
  try {
    // Next line throws if `value` is not a CallSite instance
    CallSite.prototype.toString.call( value );
    return true;
  } catch (e) {
    return false;
  }
}
```

