Title: Should the HTTP Response Stream be destroyed if it's socket closed (destroyed)?

Body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

I came across a situation where a HTTP server received a request, but this request disconnected before the server pipes content to the response stream, when the pipeline starts, this request will hangs forever (and the memory could not be released too).

```javascript
const http = require("http");
const { Readable, pipeline } = require("stream");
const { promisify } = require("util");

const modernPipeline = promisify(pipeline);

const serverPort = 8233;
const serverHost = `127.0.0.1:${serverPort}`;

function sleep(msecs) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, msecs));
}

http
  .createServer(async function (request, response) {
    // We will be focusing on this route:
    if (request.url === "/timeout") {
      console.log(`[/timeout] request received`);

      // Wait for a couple seconds, you should cancel your request during this period.
      await sleep(3000);
      console.log(`[/timeout] slept`);

      try {
        // This pipeline will hang forever...
        await modernPipeline(Readable.from(["hello", " ", "world"]), response);

        console.log("[/timeout] responded");
      } catch (err) {
        // No error will be thrown.
        console.error(`[/timeout] error:`, err);
      }

      return;
    }

    // Ignore other requests.
    response.writeHead(200, { "Content-Type": "text/plain" });
    response.end("nothing here", "utf-8");
  })
  .listen(serverPort);

console.log(`server started: ${serverHost}`);
```

I submitted [this issue](https://github.com/nodejs/help/issues/3524) two days ago, but I think maybe this is a feature request: should the `response.socket.destroyed` event be bubbling up to the `response.destroyed`? (So the  `#pipeline` could detect it and throw an error.)

**Describe the solution you'd like**

The `#pipeline` in this example should throw an error.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**

The whole **Stream** concept is very powerful but not easy to grasp, we should make use-patterns more dummy-proof (as in my example, it causes memory leaks).

body:
### Version

14 / 16

### Platform

x64 macOS / Linux

### Subsystem

vm

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

```js
'use strict';

let times = 0;

function run() {
  let str = 'var a = "';
  for (let i = 0; i < 100 * 1024 / 18; i++) str += Math.random().toString();
  str += '";';

  const script = new (require('vm').Script)(str);
  times++;
  if (times % 1000 === 0) console.log(times);
}

(async () => {
  while (true) {
    run();

    await new Promise(resolve => {
      setTimeout(() => {
        resolve();
      }, 10);
    });

    gc();
  }
})();
```

Run with:

```bash
$ node --expose-gc --max-heap-size=100 test.js
```

It will occur heap OOM under Node.js 14 and 16, and **Node.js 12 is OK**.

```
<--- Last few GCs --->                                                         
                                                                                                                                                               
[1430950:0x55695b1dc4b0]     6372 ms: Mark-sweep 72.0 (91.6) -> 71.6 (91.8) MB, 4.3 / 0.0 ms  (average mu = 0.728, current mu = 0.778) testing GC in old space requested
[1430950:0x55695b1dc4b0]     6388 ms: Mark-sweep 72.2 (91.8) -> 71.8 (92.1) MB, 3.1 / 0.0 ms  (average mu = 0.760, current mu = 0.804) testing GC in old space requested
