1. Import overrides _only_ take effect within the module graph starting from the `vm.runIn*Context` code.
2. Any non-overridden modules within this module graph would still load _their_ imports from the override set.  (That is, if `../index.js` loaded `other-module` that did `import {readFile} from 'node:fs'`, it would get our mocked copy.)  It's _possible_ to work around this (eg `require-inject` does not provide this guarantee) but it makes the loading much more complicated when you want to override a module that's used in many places.

This is of course extremely verbose and low-level, but serves as a building block upon which more ergonomic features can be built.  The way this would look in node-tap, for example, would be something like:

```js
