body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

I use `events` module to implement a producer-consumer model, the code is below:

```javascript
const EventEmitter = require('events');

class Queue extends EventEmitter {
  constructor() {
    super();
    this.fifo = [];
  }

  release(resource) {
    this.fifo.push(resource);
    this.emit('release');
  }

  async acquire() {
    if (this.fifo.length > 0) {
      return Promise.resolve(this.fifo.shift());
    }
    return new Promise((resolve) => {
      this.once('release', () => {
        this.acquire().then(resolve);
      });
    });
  }
}

const queue = new Queue();

function producer() {
  queue.release('resource');
}

async function consumer() {
  const resource = await queue.acquire();
  console.log(resource);
}
```

When the resource is insufficient, once the producer releases a resource, all consumers will be woken up. So, I want to emit a specified number(like one) of listeners to consume when the resources are released.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

The `EventEmitter` class adds a method that can emit a specified number of listeners. A possible implementation is like [this](https://github.com/twchn/node/compare/master...events).

### What alternatives have you considered?

The `EventEmitter` class adds a method that can emit only one listener.

