body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

When a new Node.js core library is added, there isn't an easy way to detect if it is available other than just trying the require or import, falling back to a polyfill or alternative path if not available:

```js
try {
  var fancyNewCoreLib = await import('node:fancy-new-core-lib');
}
catch {
  fancyNewCoreLib = await import('fancy-new-core-lib-polyfill');
}
```

We do have imports and exports fallback arrays supported in the resolution system, which allow treating validation failures as fallbacks. A missing core library could be considered to be a validation failure as no file system access is needed to do the validation.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

The feature would be to support `node:[core]` style URLs in package imports and exports resolution so they can be used in these resolutions and in fallbacks, allowing a natural feature detection:

package.json
```json
{
  "imports": {
    "#feature": ["node:feature", "./feature.js"]
  },
  "exports": {
    "./feature": ["node:feature", "./feature.js"]
  }
}
```

Where `import 'pkg/feature'` or `import '#feature'` would load `node:feature` if that is a defined Node.js core module, falling back to `./feature.js` if not.

In all current Node.js versions today, the above will load `feature.js` already allowing this workflow to be used for polyfilling and feature detection of core modules.

### What alternatives have you considered?

Alternative dynamic code is as described in the first example.

// cc @nodejs/modules

