body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

I opened this issue https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/44028 speaking of how the chunks are being consumed differently in Async Generator Functions and Writable/Transform streams.
```js
const data = `
,band_name,fans,formed,origin,split,style
0,Iron Maiden,4195,1975,United Kingdom,-,"New wave of british heavy,Heavy"
1,Opeth,4147,1990,Sweden,1990,"Extreme progressive,Progressive rock,Progressive"
`

// just simulating a big stream with many chunks
const getReadable = () => new stream.Readable({
  read() {
    for (const item of data.split('\n')) this.push(item)
    this.push(null)
  }
})
```


When using Writable class it prints the output as expected:
```js
await stream.promises.pipeline(
  getReadable(),
  stream.Writable({
    write(chunk, enc, cb) {
      console.log('[classicClass] line', chunk.toString())
      console.log()
      cb(null, chunk)
    },
  }),
)
/*
line ,band_name,fans,formed,origin,split,style
line 0,Iron Maiden,4195,1975,United Kingdom,-,"New wave of british heavy,Heavy"
line 1,Opeth,4147,1990,Sweden,1990,"Extreme progressive,Progressive rock,Progressive"
*/
```
When using an Async Iterator function the whole chunk goes into a single line

```js
await stream.promises.pipeline(
  getReadable(),
  async function* (s) {
    for await (const chunk of s) {
      console.log('[asyncIterator] line', chunk.toString())
      console.log()
    }
  },
)
/*
line ,band_name,fans,formed,origin,split,style0,Iron Maiden,4195,1975,United Kingdom,-,"New wave of british heavy,Heavy"1,Opeth,4147,1990,Sweden,1990,"Extreme progressive,Progressive rock,Progressive"
*/
```

See [full example](https://gist.github.com/ErickWendel/35e30519bea728ee692089c5631f9fe4)

[@climba03](https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/44028#issuecomment-1198949126) suggested here that they're actually using two different ways to consume data.

In their words:
> I believe the main difference here is that.
When you pipe to a Writable, it will be using [.pipe or data event](https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/e5add6659d39568c23319508aaf2efe17ca65295/lib/internal/streams/pipeline.js#L323).
When you pipe to a function, it will be using [readable event](https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/e5add6659d39568c23319508aaf2efe17ca65295/lib/internal/streams/pipeline.js#L262-L263).


As a `.pipe` function could receive both functions/classes I believe they should have the same behavior as one could replace another.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

When piping to a Writable or piping to an Async Function, it should use the same approach to consume data and have the same chunk size

### What alternatives have you considered?

_No response_

### Version

v16.13.1

### Platform

Microsoft Windows NT 10.0.19044.0 x64

### Subsystem

_No response_

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Hello, I've found interesting bug on Node.js CLI on Windows Console and also on WSL.

These code will work as intended when being run inside a file (`node index.js`) or copy to CLI simultaneously, but won't work if we run it line by line.
```js
const arr = [/asd/,/cvb/];

first=`${arr.toString()}`;
console.log({first});

arr.toString();

second=`${arr.toString()}`;
console.log({second});
```

After running `arr.toString();` without assigning to a variable, the `arr` variable will broke and failed to return correct string.

### Output
**Scenario: `node index.js`**
```js
{ first: '/asd/,/cvb/' }
{ second: '/asd/,/cvb/' }
```

**Scenario: Copy to Node.js CLI simultaneously**
```js
Welcome to Node.js v16.13.1.
Type ".help" for more information.
> const arr = [/asd/,/cvb/];
undefined
>
> first=`${arr.toString()}`;
'/asd/,/cvb/'
> console.log({first});
{ first: '/asd/,/cvb/' }
undefined
>
> arr.toString();
'/asd/,/cvb/'
>
> second=`${arr.toString()}`;
'/asd/,/cvb/'
> console.log({second});
{ second: '/asd/,/cvb/' }
undefined
>
```

**Bugged Scenario: Run Line by Line on Node.js CLI**
```js
Welcome to Node.js v16.13.1.
Type ".help" for more information.
> const arr = [/asd/,/cvb/];
undefined
> first=`${arr.toString()}`;
'/asd/,/cvb/'
> console.log({first});
{ first: '/asd/,/cvb/' }
undefined
>
> arr.toString();
''
>
> second=`${arr.toString()}`;
''
> console.log({second});
{ second: '' }
undefined
>
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

On right condition, it happens all the time.

### What is the expected behavior?

`arr` variable does not change internally and able to return correct string using `.toString()` method.

### What do you see instead?

`arr.toString()` returns blank string and becomes broken.

### Additional information

_No response_

