body:
as you might know (from my issue and PRs) I'm quite interested in streams and while reading the streams and fs streams code I had the following question

let's say I have the following code:
```js
import fs from 'node:fs';
import {setTimeout} from 'node:timers/promises'
import {Readable} from 'node:stream';

async function* generate() {
    let i = 0;
    let text = '';
    while (true) {
        console.log(i);

        const result = `${i++}\n`;

        text += result;

        if(text.length >= 100) {
            console.log('wait for update for 3s');

            await setTimeout(3000);
            console.log('finish waiting');

            text = '';
        }

        yield result;
    }
}

Readable.from(generate(), {objectMode: false})
    .pipe(fs.createWriteStream('./test.txt', {highWaterMark: 100}));
```

From what I understand from the node.js code, If I quit the application (`CTRL` + `C`) before the internal write buffer with the size of the passed `highWaterMark`, the file won't contain the written data because it will still be in the buffer, but when I run this code the file is updated

I don't see in the code any listening to exit event and stuff.

and also if I change this:
```diff
-        if(text.length >= 100) {
-            console.log('wait for update for 3s');
-
-            await setTimeout(3000);
-            console.log('finish waiting');
-
-            text = '';
-        }
- 
+        if(text.length >= 100) {
+            process.exit(0);
+        }
```

the file is not updated 🤔 

Could someone please help me understand the internal code 😄

text:
Title: streams Implementation question

Body:
as you might know (from my issue and PRs) I'm quite interested in streams and while reading the streams and fs streams code I had the following question

let's say I have the following code:
```js
import fs from 'node:fs';
import {setTimeout} from 'node:timers/promises'
import {Readable} from 'node:stream';

async function* generate() {
    let i = 0;
    let text = '';
    while (true) {
        console.log(i);

        const result = `${i++}\n`;

        text += result;

        if(text.length >= 100) {
            console.log('wait for update for 3s');

            await setTimeout(3000);
            console.log('finish waiting');

            text = '';
        }

        yield result;
    }
}

Readable.from(generate(), {objectMode: false})
    .pipe(fs.createWriteStream('./test.txt', {highWaterMark: 100}));
```

From what I understand from the node.js code, If I quit the application (`CTRL` + `C`) before the internal write buffer with the size of the passed `highWaterMark`, the file won't contain the written data because it will still be in the buffer, but when I run this code the file is updated

I don't see in the code any listening to exit event and stuff.

and also if I change this:
```diff
-        if(text.length >= 100) {
-            console.log('wait for update for 3s');
-
-            await setTimeout(3000);
-            console.log('finish waiting');
-
-            text = '';
-        }
- 
+        if(text.length >= 100) {
+            process.exit(0);
+        }
```

the file is not updated 🤔 

Could someone please help me understand the internal code 😄

