Title: Will Node.js support transferring Inspector protocol data transparently over `inspector.Session` ?

Body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

This capability allows users to implement custom inspector features, such as communicating with the target thread directly through chrome dev tools or a custom client without opening the debug port 🤔.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

I think we can implement this by the code as follows,  `inspector.Session` can also inherit from `RawSession`.

```js
class RawSession extends EventEmitter {
  constructor() {
    super();
    this[connectionSymbol] = null;
  }

  connect() {
    if (this[connectionSymbol])
      throw new ERR_INSPECTOR_ALREADY_CONNECTED('The inspector session');
    this[connectionSymbol] =
      new Connection((message) => this[onMessageSymbol](message));
  }

  [onMessageSymbol](message) {
    this.emit('message', message);
  }

  post(message) {
    if (!this[connectionSymbol]) {
      throw new ERR_INSPECTOR_NOT_CONNECTED();
    }
    this[connectionSymbol].dispatch(message);
  }

  disconnect() {
    if (!this[connectionSymbol])
      return;
    this[connectionSymbol].disconnect();
    this[connectionSymbol] = null;
  }
}
```

### What alternatives have you considered?

_No response_

body:
### Version

v18.14.1

### Platform

Linux 703748a51615 5.18.8-051808-generic #202206290850 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Wed Jun 29 08:59:08 UTC 2022 x86_64 Linux

### Subsystem

stream

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

```js
const stream = require("node:stream");
const consumers = require("node:stream/consumers");
const createInnerTransfrom = () => new stream.Transform({
    objectMode: true,
    construct(callback) {
        this.push('header from constructor\n');
        callback();
    },
    transform: (row, encoding, callback) => {
        callback(null, JSON.stringify(row) + '\n');
    },
});
const createOuterTransfrom = () => {
    let innerTranfrorm;
    return new stream.Transform({
        objectMode: true,
        transform(row, encoding, callback) {
            if (!innerTranfrorm) {
                innerTranfrorm = createInnerTransfrom();
                innerTranfrorm.on('data', (data) => this.push(data));
                callback();
            }
            else if (innerTranfrorm.write(row)) {
                process.nextTick(callback);
            }
            else {
                innerTranfrorm.once('drain', callback);
            }
        },
    });
};
consumers.text(stream.Readable.from([
    'create InnerTransform',
    'firstLine',
    'secondLine',
]).pipe(createOuterTransfrom())).then((text) => console.log('output:\n', text));
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

always

### What is the expected behavior?

```
output:
 header from constructor
"firstLine"
"secondLine"

```

### What do you see instead?

```
output:
 header from constructor
"secondLine"
"firstLine"

```

### Additional information

I expect `Transform` to **always** process incoming items in order, even with reckless code like in the example.

