Title: Add a promise-based API and a synchronous API to the stream module

Body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

Recently, I used the idea of this great [Stack Overflow post](https://stackoverflow.com/a/7443587/2326961) to configure a Node HTTP service application in a flexible way from command-line, environment, and file with `CommandLineConfig`, `EnvironmentConfig`, and `FileConfig` classes.

My `FileConfig` class has a `constructor(path)` method taking a path to a configuration file and has a `get(key)` method taking a key of a value to look up in the configuration file. The problem with the design of that class is that initialization with a path is not convenient to unit test since it requires interacting with the filesystem during the tests (thereby low performing and cluttering up the filesystem with temporary files) or mock the functions of the `fs` module which are called by the class’s implementation (thereby coupling the tests to the implementation).

```javascript
import fs from 'node:fs';


class FileConfig {

  constructor(path) {
    this.config = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(path));
  }

  get(key) {
    return this.config[key];
  }
}
```

Application:

```javascript
import {App} from './app.js';
import {FileConfig} from './config.js';

config = new FileConfig('config.json');
app = new App(config.get('host'), config.get('port'));
app.start();
```

Unit tests:

```javascript
import assert from 'node:assert/strict';
import test from 'node:test';

import {FileConfig} from '../src/config.js';

test.test(
  () => {
    config = new FileConfig('config.json');
    assert.equal(config.get('host'), 'localhost');
    assert.equal(config.get('port'), 8000);
  }
);
```

So I decided to use streams instead of paths because they are more general as they can be file streams but also network streams and in-memory streams, letting the client decide, and in particular in-memory streams are what I’m after for unit tests. So I updated the `constructor(readableStream)` method to take a readable stream over a configuration file.

```javascript
import fs from 'node:fs';


class FileConfig {

  constructor(readableStream) {
    this.readableStream = readableStream;
  }

  async get(key) {
    if (!this.config) {
      this.config = JSON.parse(await read(this.readableStream));
    }
    return this.config[key];
  }
}


function read(readableStream) {
  return new Promise(
    (resolve, reject) => {
      let data = '';
      readableStream.on(
        'readable', () => {
          let chunk;
          while (chunk = readableStream.read()) {
            data += chunk;
          }
        }
      );
      readableStream.on(
        'end', () => {
          resolve(data);
        }
      );
      readableStream.on(
        'error', (error) => {
          reject(error);
        }
      );
    }
  );
}
```

Application:

```javascript
import {App} from './app.js';
import {FileConfig} from './config.js';

config = new FileConfig('config.json');
app = new App(await config.get('host'), await config.get('port'));
app.start();
```

Unit tests:

```javascript
import assert from 'node:assert/strict';
import stream from 'node:stream';
import test from 'node:test';

import {FileConfig} from '../src/config.js';

test.test(
  async () => {
    const readableStream = stream.Readable.from('{"host": "localhost", "port": 8000}');
    const config = new FileConfig(readableStream);
    assert.equal(await config.get('host'), 'localhost');
    assert.equal(await config.get('port'), 8000);
  }
);
```

The stream approach works great, but **the `stream` module only has a callback-based API so I have two problems with it:**

- **it does not have a promise-based API** (contrary to `fs` which already has `fs/promises`) so it requires me to write the `read(readableStream)` function above;
- **it does not have a synchronous API** (contrary to `fs` which already has both asynchronous and synchronous functions) so it requires me to make the `get(key)` method above asynchronous, cluttering up top-level code with `await` keywords for simple configuration at application startup.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

Add a promise-based API and a synchronous API to the `stream` module, which currently has only a callback-based API. For reference, the `fs` module already has the three APIs.

### What alternatives have you considered?

Using the existing callback-based API of the `stream` module like described in the stream implementation above.

body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

I often use Node.js stream components to solve both personal and work-related problems.

I saw myself working with `Promise`s and `async` code a lot, and, to simplify this use-case, I created a simple [wrapper](https://github.com/greguz/fluido#stream-with-asyncawait) for the `node:stream` module that let the developer use the `async` keyword within the stream implementation methods (`_write`, `_finish`, `_construct`, etc).

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

Everything could be exported by the `node:stream/promises` module.

The implementation is dead simple, and It's something like that:

```javascript
import * as stream from 'node:stream'

function isPromiseLike (value) {
  return typeof Object(value).then === 'function'
}

function handlePromise (fn) {
  if (typeof fn !== 'function') {
    return fn
  }
  return Object.defineProperty(
    function (...args) {
      const callback = args[args.length - 1] // args.pop() to "hide" the callback
      const value = fn.call(this, ...args)
      if (isPromiseLike(value)) {
        value.then(
          result => callback(null, result),
          callback
        )
      }
    },
    'name',
    { value: fn.name }
  )
}

// export as 'node:stream/promises'
export class Writable extends stream.Writable {
  constructor (options) {
    super(options)

    // override internal properties to support the `.prototype._write = function () {}` usage
    this._write = handlePromise(this._write)
    // and so on for the other methods...
  }
}

// plus the other stream classes (Readable, Duplex, and Transform)
```

I think that this feature could simplify the usage of the `node:stream` module while using promised code.

The usage will be something like this:

```javascript
import { Writable } from 'node:stream/promises'

const w = new Writable({
  async write (chunk) {
    await doSomething(chunk)
  }
})
```

...and with "extend class" way...

```javascript
import { Writable } from 'node:stream/promises'

class MyWritable extends Writable {
  async _write (chunk) {
    await doSomething(chunk)
  }
}

const w = new MyWritable()
```

The only thing that I'm not totally sure If I had implemented well enough to be included inside Node.js itself is the `Readable`'s `_read` method. That method doesn't use callbacks, so I used a solution similar to other packages like [`from2`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/from2):

```javascript
import * as stream from 'node:stream'

import { isPromiseLike } from './promise.mjs'
import { once } from './util.mjs'

// map an async read method (asyncRead) to its "sync" version to be used by the stream
function createReadMethod (asyncRead) {
  let reading = false

  return function _read (size) {
    if (reading) {
      return
    }
    reading = true

    const callback = once((err, data) => {
      reading = false

      // Detects manual .push(null) and .destroy()
      const alive = !this.closed && !this.readableEnded
      if (!alive) {
        return
      }

      if (err) {
        // This will set `closed` to true
        return this.destroy(err)
      }

      if (data !== undefined) {
        // If null, this will set `readableEnded` to true
        this.push(data)
      }

      if (
        data !== null &&
        this.readableFlowing &&
        this.readableLength < this.readableHighWaterMark
      ) {
        // We have room inside the buffer
        process.nextTick(() => this._read(size))
      }
    })

    const out = asyncRead.call(this, size, callback)
    if (isPromiseLike(out)) {
      out.then(
        result => callback(null, result),
        callback
      )
    }
  }
}

export class Readable extends stream.Readable {
  constructor (options) {
    super(options)

    this._read = createReadMethod(this._read)
    // and so on for the other methods...
  }
}
```

Implementing new code inside `node:stream/promises` will also avoid potential performance problems that could emerge by changing something inside the core `node:stream` module (too much code depending on).

I'm also available to do some PR.

### What alternatives have you considered?

_No response_

