body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

Many popular packages throw errors in a way that truncates the stack trace at the package's own code. This can make it extremely difficult to debug such exceptions, as the original stack trace is lost. Unfortunately, in many cases, the contributors to these packages reject requests to fix the issue and improve the stack trace.  Examples:
- https://github.com/axios/axios/issues/2387
- https://github.com/stripe/stripe-node/issues/1066

⚠️ This problem exists because package authors do not take advantage of the async stack trace. Using the [return await](https://github.com/goldbergyoni/nodebestpractices#-212-always-await-promises-before-returning-to-avoid-a-partial-stacktrace) approach does not solve this problem.  Most of these stack traces are truncated `at processTicksAndRejections (node:internal/process/task_queues`⚠️

General solution is add to user's code try catch block and re-throw new Error with cause.
Friendly reminder we have [Error: cause](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Error/cause).

I use the following helper in all of my projects:
```typescript
async function reThrowOnError<T>(promise: Promise<T>, errorConstructor: ErrorConstructor = Error): Promise<T> {
  try {
    return await promise;
  } catch (error) {
    const errorMessage = error instanceof Error ? error.message : errorConstructor.name;
    const capturedError = new errorConstructor(errorMessage, { cause: error });
    Error.captureStackTrace(capturedError, reThrowOnError);
    throw capturedError;
  }
}
```

Usage example:
```typescript
    const session = await reThrowOnError(stripeClient.billingPortal.sessions.create({customer: 'df'}));
```

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

I have been thinking about:
1. helper `node:util.errorify` or `node:util.reThrowOnError` like i described at the problem block.
2. `node:util.errorifyAll` or `node:util.reThrowOnErrorAll` what will wrap the object, so every method will be wrapped with reThrowOnError. Inspired by bluebird.promiseAll

### What alternatives have you considered?

I have been thinking about a userland module. I'll go this route if the contributors decide that this functionality is not needed in the Node.js core.

