Title: Feature request: add ability to avoid missed stack traces

Body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

Many popular packages throw errors in a way that truncates the stack trace at the package's own code. This can make it extremely difficult to debug such exceptions, as the original stack trace is lost. Unfortunately, in many cases, the contributors to these packages reject requests to fix the issue and improve the stack trace.  Examples:
- https://github.com/axios/axios/issues/2387
- https://github.com/stripe/stripe-node/issues/1066

⚠️ This problem exists because package authors do not take advantage of the async stack trace. Using the [return await](https://github.com/goldbergyoni/nodebestpractices#-212-always-await-promises-before-returning-to-avoid-a-partial-stacktrace) approach does not solve this problem.  Most of these stack traces are truncated `at processTicksAndRejections (node:internal/process/task_queues`⚠️

General solution is add to user's code try catch block and re-throw new Error with cause.
Friendly reminder we have [Error: cause](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Error/cause).

I use the following helper in all of my projects:
```typescript
async function reThrowOnError<T>(promise: Promise<T>, errorConstructor: ErrorConstructor = Error): Promise<T> {
  try {
    return await promise;
  } catch (error) {
    const errorMessage = error instanceof Error ? error.message : errorConstructor.name;
    const capturedError = new errorConstructor(errorMessage, { cause: error });
    Error.captureStackTrace(capturedError, reThrowOnError);
    throw capturedError;
  }
}
```

Usage example:
```typescript
    const session = await reThrowOnError(stripeClient.billingPortal.sessions.create({customer: 'df'}));
```

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

I have been thinking about:
1. helper `node:util.errorify` or `node:util.reThrowOnError` like i described at the problem block.
2. `node:util.errorifyAll` or `node:util.reThrowOnErrorAll` what will wrap the object, so every method will be wrapped with reThrowOnError. Inspired by bluebird.promiseAll

### What alternatives have you considered?

I have been thinking about a userland module. I'll go this route if the contributors decide that this functionality is not needed in the Node.js core.

body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

Zlib compression is inherently a CPU-bound task. Therefore, it's only logical that when you need to compress lots of things, you'd want to utilize all your CPUs. However, Node.js's built-in [`zlib`](https://nodejs.org/api/zlib.html) module does compression within [`libuv`](https://github.com/libuv/libuv)'s thread pool, which is designed for I/O-bound tasks, not CPU-bound tasks. In fact, `libuv` spawns exactly `4` threads by default; it has no correlation to the number of CPUs available.

Node.js does provide [synchronous convenience methods](https://nodejs.org/api/zlib.html#zlibgzipsyncbuffer-options) which do the work in the current thread. This, in combination with [`worker_threads`](https://nodejs.org/api/worker_threads.html), allows you to actually utilize all your CPUs for bulk compression tasks. Unfortunately, these synchronous methods are unable to process chunks piecewise; if you need to compress a large file, you have to put the entire thing into memory.

Therefore, if you need to compress many large files, Node.js provides no public API for doing it in an optimal way.

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

I propose a new API within the built-in `zlib` module which allows you to synchronously compress data, chunk-by-chunk. The API can mirror the existing [`Hash`](https://nodejs.org/api/crypto.html#class-hash) class that's provided by the `crypto` module.

```js
const zlib = require('node:zlib');

const gzip = new zlib.GzipSync();

// Each update() call returns the available output, if any (could be an empty Buffer)
const compressedOutput1 = gzip.update(chunk1);
const compressedOutput2 = gzip.update(chunk2);

// The digest() call flushes the output and returns the last output chunk
const compressedOutput3 = gzip.digest();

// The complete result is just the concatenation of all output Buffers
const result = Buffer.concat([compressedOutput1, compressedOutput2, compressedOutput3]);

```

An example of real-world usage might look like this:

```js
const fs = require('node:fs'); 
const zlib = require('node:zlib');

const CHUNK_SIZE = 1024 * 16;

function* gzipFile(filename, zlibOptions) {
	const gzip = new zlib.GzipSync(zlibOptions);
	const fd = fs.openSync(filename);
	try {
		while (true) {
			const buffer = Buffer.alloc(CHUNK_SIZE);
			const bytesRead = fs.readSync(fd, buffer, 0, CHUNK_SIZE);
			if (bytesRead > 0) {
				yield gzip.update(buffer.subarray(0, bytesRead));
			}
			if (bytesRead < CHUNK_SIZE) {
				yield gzip.digest();
				break;
			}
		}
	} finally {
		fs.closeSync(fd);
	}
}
```

### What alternatives have you considered?

I have searched [npm](https://www.npmjs.com/) and found only two packages that claim to achieve this while using native zlib bindings:

- https://github.com/isaacs/minizlib
- https://github.com/timotejroiko/fast-zlib

Both of these packages utilize very scary, dirty hacks around the undocumented [`_processChunk()`](https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/main/lib/zlib.js#L427) method, and manipulating the undocumented `_handle` property (which holds the native zlib instance), used internally by Node.js. I don't find these solutions to be remotely safe or future-proof.

