body:
### What is the problem this feature will solve?

When using `pipeline(alreadyConsumed, ...)` with a stream that was already consumed (`_readableState.ended = true`), the `pipeline` will succeed and act as if the input was a readable stream that yields no data (= "empty stream").

Clearly a readable should not be read twice but protecting against such cases can yield better DX.

One example of such case can be see in googleapis/nodejs-storage [here](https://github.com/googleapis/nodejs-storage/pull/2203/files#diff-bc9705d0f7a567399044dfc66ccc82d4d9aa1cff116842a0094d54e463c9ecbcR3617-R3624). In this example, the library author needs to manually check (and throw) if the pipeline operation would not perform the intended behavior. This could be done by `pipeline` by default IMHO.

```js
const stream = require('stream');
const {pipeline} = require('stream/promises');

async function main() {
  const readable = stream.Readable({
    read() {
      this.push('aaa');
      this.push(null);
    },
  });

  readable.read();

  console.log(readable.destroyed); // false
  console.log(readable._readableState.ended); // true

  await new Promise((resolve) => setImmediate(resolve));

  console.log(readable.destroyed); // true
  console.log(readable._readableState.ended); // true

  await pipeline(readable, async function* (source) {
    for await (const chunk of source) {
      console.log('chunk', chunk); // Never called
    }
    console.log('done');
  });
}

main();

```

### What is the feature you are proposing to solve the problem?

`pipeline` should throw an error if the input is a readable stream that was already consumed / destroyed.

### What alternatives have you considered?

- Improve the docs to explain that a pipeline with a consumed readable would not yield expected results

